## Cursor — Backend Development Rules (Abhedyam MVP)

1. Implement only finalized features listed in the project record.
2. Do not create extra APIs, endpoints, or modules unless explicitly mentioned.
3. Keep every change focused and minimal — one purpose per generation.
4. Follow DRY — reuse existing logic and avoid duplication.
5. Maintain clean, small files with clear names; modular code > monolithic blobs.
6. No comments inside generated code — readability through clean structure only.
7. Always update or generate OpenAPI spec for public endpoints.
8. Prefix all API routes with versioning (`/api/v1/...`).
9. Use consistent response envelopes for errors and optional success; include machine-readable error codes.
10. Generate unit tests for business logic covering success, edge, and failure paths.
11. Tests must be deterministic and run without external dependencies (mock gateways & APIs).
12. Include contract validation tests (responses vs OpenAPI).
13. Create light integration tests only for critical flows (auth, sale, payment, notification).
14. Never expose secrets or credentials in code — use env/config placeholders only.
15. Validate and sanitize all incoming data; reject malformed or unsafe input.
16. Use structured JSON logs; include `requestId`/`correlationId` where available; never log sensitive fields.
17. Design APIs and flows with idempotency for payment/OTP endpoints.
18. Use a message queue only if needed. Generate worker scaffolds only when explicitly requested.
19. During development, DB schema changes can fully overwrite old versions — latest schema is truth.
20. Generate proper API contracts and specs (OpenAPI must always match code).
21. Until MVP: no PR flow needed — just build and commit clean.
22. If any ambiguity or assumption arises, ask first before generating code.
23. Minimal metrics: expose only core counters (sales_created, otp_sent, payment_attempts).
24. CI-ready structure: include tests, OpenAPI validation, lint.
25. Maintain small, focused prompt templates in `/.ai/prompts.md`.
26. When generating code, list affected files + brief purpose (1–2 lines), no code explanations.
